    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">loanDepot will not accept the deed book and page number as a legal description.</span></li>

<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">Exposure Time &amp; Prior Services</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">To adhere to USPAP guidelines, the appraisal must contain a statement indicating a reasonable exposure time for the subject <em>at the indicated value</em>.</span></li>
    <li><span style="background: white; font-size: 10pt; letter-spacing: 0.4pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">As required by USPAP, the appraisal must include a statement indicating whether or not any services as an appraiser or in any other capacity regarding the property that is the subject of this report within the three-year period immediately preceding acceptance of this assignment have been performed.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Disasters</span></strong></p>
<p><em><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Note: reporting requirements are applicable when the subject property is included in an area identified by FEMA as a disaster area.</span></em></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraiser to comment on any disasters that have occurred in the County of the subject property over the prior 120 days.</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The appraiser is required to comment on any damage to the subject property and the subject’s neighborhood caused by the disaster and to comment on any impact to marketability or value. </span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If applicable, appraiser to provide photos of any disaster damage. This includes damage to the subject property or the market area which can include - but is not limited to - damaged streets, power lines, utility systems, flooding, etc.</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">When possible, the appraisal should use sales that transpired after the disaster. However, if there are not sufficient post-disaster comparable sales or listings, then appraiser must provide current photos of the comparables. MLS photos or photos previously taken by appraiser prior to the disaster are unacceptable.</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If the appraisal inspection was completed before a declared disaster, a property re-inspection by the appraiser may be required. </span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The re-inspection report must comment whether the property is “safe, sound, and sanitary” for the occupants and if the value of the property has been adversely impacted.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If re-inspection finds damage, then damage must be described and photographed, an estimated cost to cure provided, and an additional re-inspection requested to evidence completion of necessary repairs. </span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Land Subsidence &amp; Sinkholes</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The appraiser must analyze and report any readily observable conditions of the surface of the land that indicate potential problems. While not required to be an expert in the field of environmental hazards, the appraiser is responsible for noting any adverse conditions observed during the inspection or made aware of while performing due diligence. In the event of a sinkhole on the subject site, the appraiser must provide photographs of the impacted area.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Site and Zoning</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">The appraisal analysis must include any adverse effect that non-conforming use has on the value and marketability of the property. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">An appraisal with illegal zoning compliance will not deliver through the FNC portal. see “Assignment &amp; Property Issues” section above.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">If site dimensions are not provided in the appraisal, the appraiser must provide the plat map and identify the subject parcel on the plat map. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">No hypothetical lot sizes are allowed. The subject property is to be appraised according to legal records unless otherwise instructed.</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If appraiser is provided a survey of site changes currently in progress, the appraiser must contact loanDepot for further instruction, for title may need to be revised and the survey recorded with the local governing authority. </span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Irregular lot shapes and any easements are to be noted in the report and on the plat map.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Multiple Parcels</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Additional parcels may be included in the appraisal report.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">An adjoining parcel may not have an additional dwelling unit. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Each parcel must be conveyed in its entirety, and all parcels must be contiguous (exception being if parcels are divided by a road and the divided parcel is non-buildable).</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Each parcel must have the same basic zoning (for example, residential, agricultural).</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">All parcels encumbered in title are to be valued in their entirety, for the mortgage is a valid first lien that covers each parcel so that multiple parcels – when encumbered - cannot be separated.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: red;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Highest &amp; Best Use</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">The appraiser’s highest &amp; best use analysis of the subject property should consider the property as it is improved. This treatment recognizes that the existing improvements should continue in the current use until it is financially feasible to remove the dwelling and build a new one or to renovate the existing dwelling. </span><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If the use of comparable sales demonstrates that the improvements are reasonably typical and compatible with market demand for the neighborhood, and the present improvements contribute to the value of the subject property so that its value is greater than the estimated vacant site value, the appraiser should consider the existing use as reasonable and report it as the highest and best use.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">If the current use is other than the highest &amp; best use, the appraiser must provide an analysis of highest &amp; best use with supporting documentation.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">If current and or highest &amp; best use of the subject is other than residential, </span><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">see “Assignment &amp; Property Issues” section above.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Subject Property &amp; Neighborhood Reporting Requirements</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraiser must comment on the subject neighborhood or subject property’s proximity to adverse influences and address said factors with comparable sales that bracket the adverse features and provide market supported adjustments as necessary. </span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Photos of such factors, including but is not limited to busy streets, proximity to freeways/airports, commercial/industrial influences, etc. must be included in the addendum.</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">For properties with acreage or an agricultural zoning, appraiser must comment if they observed any commercial, agricultural/farming, or ranching activities, and provide details/photos of their observations. Where applicable, appraiser must identify and report if the subject property is being used as a working farm (income producing) or is considered a hobby farm.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">For PUDs (Planned Unit Development), the following information is required:</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Legal name of project.</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">HOA dues and assessments (if any).</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Description of common elements and amenities for the subject and the comparable sales community.</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">When using non-PUD comparable sales provide an analysis to support the inclusion of non-PUD comparable sales.</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraiser to adequately analyze and report any current contract of sale, option, offering, or listing of the subject property. </span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraiser to confirm that the most up-to-date purchase contract has been provided. </span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Report and analyze any prior sales of the subject property for three years prior to the effective date of the appraisal.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">When subject has a prior sale within three years, appraiser to fully reconcile the prior sale price with the current opinion of value and detail any factors that have contributed to the difference.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Utilities and Off-Site Improvements</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Properties with private site utilities require the appraiser to confirm that they meet community standards, note any readily observable deficiencies, and make the appraisal “subject to” any tests or inspections needed for verification.</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If subject’s water source is not public or a drilled well (private, community, or shared), appraiser to comment if the water source is common for the market and to demonstrate market acceptance by providing a comparable with a similar water source. </span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If subject’s sewage-disposal system is not public, appraiser to comment if the sewage-disposal system is common for the market and to demonstrate market acceptance by providing a comparable with a similar sewage-disposal system. </span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If the subject is on a private road the appraiser must analyze and report the on the Road Maintenance Agreement details if available. If unavailable, the appraiser to comment whether there is adequate vehicular access and if there is an agreement of some type for vehicular access and maintenance.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If subject property is in a PUD, appraiser to comment if HOA maintains the private road.</span>
    <p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
    <p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Improvements</span></strong></p>
    </li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If the subject has any unpermitted additions (including a garage conversion), comment on the quality and appearance of the work and the impact on marketability and value, on any functional obsolescence, and on any zoning violations.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraisal should not be made subject to permits.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If a primary dwelling has an additional manufactured home on site that is not valued as an Accessory Dwelling Unit, the manufactured home cannot be permanently affixed to the site and must be considered personal property with no contributory value given.</span>
    <p><span style="background: yellow; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
    <p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Sketch/Floor Plan</span></strong></p>
    </li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraisers are required to use the ANSI® Z765-2021 standard for measuring, calculating, and reporting gross living area (GLA) and non-GLA areas of subject properties for appraisals requiring interior and exterior inspections.</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #121212;">The ANSI standard must be followed for houses with detached or attached architectural design including townhouses, rowhouses, and other side-by-side houses</span><span style="font-size: 9pt; font-family: SourceSansPro-Light, sans-serif; color: #121212;">.</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Further details for ANSI® Z765-2021 can be found at </span><a href="https://singlefamily.fanniemae.com/media/30266/display"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #4472c4;">https://singlefamily.fanniemae.com/media/30266/display</span></a><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">.</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">When </span><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">unable to adhere to the ANSI Z765-2021 standard (and it is applicable), enter "GXX001-" at the beginning of the Additional Features field of the appraisal and provide an explanation of why unable to comply.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">The building sketch must contain exterior dimensions and calculations for all the subject’s levels (including basement) and for all outbuildings.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Any areas of functional obsolescence must be identified on the sketch including the use of interior walls.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Hand-drawn sketches are unacceptable.</span>
    <p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;</span></p>
    <p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Photo Requirements</span></strong></p>
    </li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Required exterior photographs</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Clear, descriptive color photographs showing the front, back, and a street scene of the subject property and the front of each comparable – including rental comparables. The subject and all comparables must be appropriately identified. </span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">Any improvements with contributory value not captured in the front or rear photographs – garages, outbuildings, etc.</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Required interior photographs</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Kitchen, main living area, all bathrooms, and all bedrooms</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Basement</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Recent updates, restoration, remodeling, and renovation</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Photos of any significant deferred maintenance and any physical deterioration that affects the property’s safety, soundness, or structural integrity and that will require additional inspection or repair.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Aerial View from a reliable source such as Google maps that is of sufficient scale to show the subject property, immediate neighborhood, and any external obsolescence.</span>
    <p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
    <p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Property Condition and Quality Reporting</span></strong></p>
    </li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Properties with Condition Ratings C1 through C5 are eligible for delivery in “as is” condition. For Properties with the initial Condition Rating of C6 and properties with one or more deficiencies that impact the safety, soundness, or the structural integrity of the property, the appraisal must be completed “Subject-to” the deficient item(s) being repaired or updated to bring the subject to a C5 or better condition.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Quality Ratings Q1 through Q5 are eligible for delivery. A property determined to be in Q6 condition may be eligible if the items noted do not affect the safety, soundness, or structural integrity of the property.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Appraiser must report and describe any deficiencies that could affect the safety, soundness, or structural integrity. If any items that are incomplete or the condition affects the safety, soundness, or structural integrity of the property, the property must be appraised “Subject-to” completion of the specific alterations or repairs and the condition and quality ratings based on the hypothetical condition that any noted items are cured or complete. </span><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If the appraiser is not qualified to evaluate the alterations or repairs needed, the appraisal must identify and describe the deficiencies and the property must be appraised subject to a satisfactory inspection by a qualified professional<span style="color: red;">.</span></span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Any photos of potential health/safety issues must also include commentary indicating whether safety, soundness or structural integrity of the property is impacted.</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Common issues that may require additional commentary: </span>
        <ul style="list-style-type: square;">
            <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Missing handrails on interior stairwells: “as is” report is acceptable if the absence does not pose a safety issue.</span></li>
        </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    </li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Missing guardrails: “as is” report is acceptable if the fall height does not pose a safety issue. Appraisal to specify the fall distance.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Security bars on windows: appraisal to comment whether windows with security bars in sleeping areas have safety release latches. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Water damage: appraisal to observe, report, and analyze the impact on marketability and value and to provide photos. Appraisal to comment on the source of the damage and if there are any active water leaks. Active leaks require a cure or a professional inspection evidencing no structural issue. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Mold-like growth: appraisal to observe, report, and analyze the impact on marketability and value and to provide photos. Lender will determine whether additional inspection or action is required. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Infestation/Dampness/Settlement: appraisal to observe, report, and analyze the impact on marketability and value and to provide photos. Either a cure or a professional inspection evidencing no structural issue is required.</span>
    <p><span style="background: yellow; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
    <p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Sales Comparison Approach &amp; Comparable Selection</span></strong></p>
    </li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Comparable Sales 1 through 3 must be closed sales, and all closed sales must have closed on or prior to the effective date of the appraisal. </span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraiser must adjust for the impact that concessions have on the sale prices per the definition of market value in all Fannie Mae/Freddie Mac appraisal forms. No adjustments are necessary for those costs which are normally paid by sellers as a result of tradition or law in a market area.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Include the following Comparable Sales list information within the appraisal report:</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Description of the search criteria used (i.e., GLA, distance, time, age, etc.)</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Explain the results of the search (i.e., GLA range, number of sales found, sales price range, etc.) then explain how the appraiser filtered the selection of sales.</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">loanDepot will accept an appraisal report that contains dated and/or distant sales. The appraiser must provide an analysis providing reasonable logic and rational for using sales that are dated and/or distant and define the search perimeters used in the search.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Unique / uncommon housing types</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Appraisal to provide at least one sale of the same design and appeal to demonstrate impact on marketability and value. Appraiser may use dated or distant sales to meet the requirement.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">If appraiser cannot locate a sale with the same design and appeal, appraisal is to provide sound support for any design and appeal adjustments (or lack thereof) to the comparable sales that are utilized.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Declining or Increasing Markets</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Analyze and report the impact on value due to the declining or increasing market condition changes.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Provide a minimum of two (2) active listings or pending sales in the grid as part of the sales comparison approach.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Apply any necessary time adjustments along with support and analysis for the time adjustments or lack thereof. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Report and analyze any prior sales of the comparables within 12 months. </span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">When an appraisal comparable has a prior sale within one year, appraiser to fully reconcile the prior sale price with the more current sale price and detail any factors that have contributed to the difference.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Accessory Dwelling Units</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Only one ADU is allowed. If the subject has more than one ADU, please contact loanDepot for further instruction. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The ADU must be subordinate in size to the primary dwelling.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">An ADU must be located on the same parcel as the main dwelling and have a means of ingress/egress, a kitchen, a sleeping area, a bathing area, and bathroom facilities. </span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The ADU may, but is not required to, include access to the primary dwelling. However, it is not considered an ADU if it can only be accessed through the primary dwelling, or the area is open to the primary dwelling with no expectation of privacy.</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="background: white; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">The construction method of an ADU can be site- or factory-built housing (including modular, and single- or multi-width manufactured homes) that are legally classified as real property. If an ADU is present, the primary dwelling must be site-built or a modular home.</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">A primary dwelling that is a manufactured home cannot have an ADU.</span>
        <p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        <p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">ADU appraisal reporting requirements:</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The ADU must be excluded from the Gross Living Area and must be valued as a separate line item in grid. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The ADU must be included on sketch</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Include photos of interior rooms and, if applicable, exterior photos.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraiser must provide a minimum of one comparable sale to demonstrate market acceptance.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraisal must comment whether ADU is allowed per zoning.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
    <li><span style="background: white; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">ADUs may predate the adoption of the local zoning ordinance and therefore be classified as legal nonconforming. </span></li>
    <li><span style="background: white; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">An ADU should always be considered legal if it is allowed under the current zoning code for the subject property.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If the ADU violates zoning: </span></li>
</ul>
<ol>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The appraisal must comment that improvements do not comply with zoning.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The appraisal report must demonstrate that the improvements are typical for the market through an analysis of at least two (2) comparable sales with the same non-compliant zoning use.</span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Second Kitchens</span></strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">When the subject property has a second kitchen in the primary dwelling, Appraiser must comment:</span>
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">If the second kitchen is allowed per zoning</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">If the second kitchen poses any health, safety, or structural integrity issues</span></li>
        <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">On the quality and appearance of the work and its impact on the subject’s marketability and/or value.</span></li>
    </ul>
    </li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">Appraisers should only observe, report, and analyze on the impact of the second kitchen. Appraisals should not be made subject to removal of the second kitchen. If a second kitchen violates zoning or if it poses a health and safety risk, that needs to be clearly stated within the report. loanDepot’s Credit Policy department will advise on how or if the issue can be cured.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Mixed Use Properties</span></strong></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">A mixed-use property has a </span><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">business use in addition to its residential use. <span style="color: #231f20;">The subject property must be primarily residential, and the borrower must be both the owner occupant and operator of the business.</span><s><span style="color: red;"> </span></s></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraisal requirements for mixed-use properties must:</span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Provide a detailed description of the mixed-use characteristics of the subject property.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Indicate that the use of the property is a legal, permissible use of the property under local zoning requirements.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Report any adverse impact on marketability and market resistance to the commercial use of the property.</span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #231f20;">Report the market value of the property based on the residential characteristics rather than on the business use or any special business-use modifications.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">New Construction Requirements</span></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">For all new construction appraisals, the appraiser must: </span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Review the most up-to-date executed purchase contract. A copy of the purchase contract is provided by loanDepot, but the appraiser is responsible to verify with the builder representative/agents that the contract they received includes the most current addendums and upgrades.</span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Discuss and analyze any lot premiums, options, and upgrades included in the sale price for the subject property and any builder comparable sales or listings.</span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Provide at least one settled comparable sale from the subject’s subdivision or PUD, or condo project; <span style="background: white; color: black;">If the subject property is part of a newly built or recently converted condo project, subdivision, or PUD that has 2-20 units and there are no settled or pending sales, the appraiser may use comparable sales from a competing project, subdivision, or PUD.</span></span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Provide at least one settled comparable sale from outside the subject’s subdivision, PUD, or condo project.</span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="background: white; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">If the subject property is not the first unit under contract in the condo project, subdivision, or PUD, the appraisal must include at least one other sale from the subject's project, subdivision, or PUD that is also under contract.</span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The appraisal must include a computer-generated sketch with exterior dimensions and area calculations.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If actual measurements cannot be obtained by appraiser, the dimensions may be taken from the blueprints or plans and specifications. </span></li>
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The floor plan must clearly identify all levels, rooms, bedrooms, bathrooms, and living areas (including basements, etc.).</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="background: white; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: black;">For appraisals that are proposed construction or are made subject to completion, the appraiser must: </span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Review the plans and specifications for the subject and the project and include a statement in the appraisal that confirms that they were reviewed.</span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Include a copy of the specifications document as an addendum in the appraisal.</span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Include a materials/features list within the report that details the kitchen and bathroom materials (cabinetry, countertops, fixtures, etc.), floor coverings, interior doors, energy-efficiency items, siding material, etc.</span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">If sufficient information is not available to the appraiser to assess subject’s interior improvements, components, upgrades and build quality, a credible appraisal cannot be completed.&nbsp; The appraiser should request that the appraisal assignment be placed on hold until the necessary information can be provided to the appraiser.&nbsp;The appraiser will request the necessary information or documentation from the loanDepot Appraisal Coordinator via AppraisalPort messaging.</span></li>
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The appraiser must inspect the subject property and will need to provide photos of the actual property from the front, rear, the street scene in both directions, and across the street from the subject. </span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">
    <li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">When subject property is in the early phases of construction, the appraisal can be supplemented with interior/exterior photos of the builder’s model home, or another completed home of the same model if the photos are labeled in a manner that clearly identifies that they are not the subject property.</span></li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
    <li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">When possible, the appraisal should contain the builder’s name and the model/floor plan.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><span style="font-size: 10pt; text-decoration: none; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;</span></strong></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Revisions and Reconsideration Requests</span></strong></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Appraiser should be aware that all appraisals are subject to review before and after loan closing. By accepting this appraisal order, the appraiser agrees to respond within two business days to all requests for revisions, clarification items, and reconsiderations. All such requests are to only be accepted when originated by the loanDepot Appraisal Department or the AMC. If the appraiser is contacted by real estate agents, loanDepot origination staff, or any other party, they should be referred to the AMC or the loanDepot Appraisal Department.</span></p><p></p>
